---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const description =
  "Infrastructure intelligence for modern compute with measurable outcomes across capacity, cost, energy, carbon, and water.";

const observations = [
  ["jobs_analyzed", "73,367"],
  ["average_efficiency_score", "25.74%"],
  ["risk_flag_jobs", "65,614"],
  ["pct_short_jobs_lt_1m", "40.95%"],
  ["pct_util_zero", "33.27%"],
  ["median_util_avg", "16.00%"]
] as const;

const excerpt = `engine: ACE v0.1
mode: msa
jobs_analyzed: 73,367
average_efficiency_score: 25.74%
risk_flag_jobs: 65,614
review_queue_a: near_zero_util
review_queue_b: over_requested
review_queue_c: runtime_variance
capacity_savings_usd: computed per run
impact_model: electricity, carbon, water`;
---

<BaseLayout title="Plain Theory Labs" description={description}>
  <section class="section prose">
    <h1>Plain Theory Labs</h1>
    <p class="thesis">Infrastructure intelligence for modern compute.</p>

    <p>Plain Theory Labs is a research and engineering lab building infrastructure engines for sustainable compute.</p>

    <p>
      We&rsquo;re researchers, engineers, and scientists who see a growing problem: AI is increasing demand for energy,
      hardware, and data centers. We build tools that help organizations understand real workload behavior and make
      practical improvements, reducing excess capacity and clarifying cost and environmental impact.
    </p>

    <p>
      We develop methods and engines that turn workload and telemetry data into transparent recommendations with
      measurable outcomes across capacity, cost, energy, carbon, and water.
    </p>

    <p class="inline-links">
      <a href="/ace">ACE Engine</a>
      <span>ACE is our first-generation engine.</span>
    </p>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>The gap</h2>
    <p>
      Teams can usually access utilization charts, but still struggle to answer operational questions with confidence:
      what changed, where is waste concentrated, and what is safe to change first under explicit assumptions.
    </p>
    <p>
      The core issue is auditability. Without clear links between recommendations and trace evidence, it is difficult
      to compare runs, verify impact, or explain decisions across operators, researchers, and institutional
      stakeholders.
    </p>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>A small slice of output</h2>
    <p class="muted">Representative excerpt from a single institutional trace analysis.</p>

    <div class="panel">
      <pre class="report-excerpt"><code>{excerpt}</code></pre>

      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Metric</th>
            <th>Value</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {observations.map(([metric, value]) => (
            <tr>
              <td><code>{metric}</code></td>
              <td>{value}</td>
            </tr>
          ))}
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p>
      These numbers are from a single system and one dataset. They are not a universal claim, just a concrete example
      of what shows up when you look closely at real workloads.
    </p>
    <p>
      Many jobs are short, and that matters operationally. Short jobs can vanish in broad averages while still
      dominating scheduling pressure and overhead decisions.
    </p>
    <p>
      Low or near-zero utilization signals, together with risk flags and a low median utilization, indicate review
      candidates. Common causes include over-requesting, idle allocation, missing telemetry, or workload mismatch.
    </p>

    <p class="muted">Interpretation depends on telemetry quality, workload mix, and how utilization is measured.</p>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>Science is better when shared</h2>
    <p>
      Scientific and engineering progress is collective. We publish methods, schemas, and write-ups when it is safe
      to share, with a focus on reproducibility and clear assumptions so others can inspect and improve the work.
    </p>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>Solid foundations matter</h2>
    <p>
      Infrastructure quality sets the ceiling for research productivity. We prioritize reliability, auditability, and
      long-horizon maintainability, so operators can trust what changed, why it changed, and what evidence supports
      it.
    </p>

    <p class="inline-links"><a href="/contact">Contact</a></p>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
